natural problem: What is the greatest common divisor of $2^{1998}-1$ and $2^{1989}-1$?
natural solution: By the Euclidean algorithm, it follows that \begin{align} \text{gcd}\,(m,n) &= \text{gcd}\,(n,m-2^9n) \\ &= \text{gcd}\,(n,2^9-1). \\ \end{align}Since $9$ divides $1998$, by the difference of odd powers factorization, it follows that $2^{1989}-1$ is divisible by $2^9 - 1$.
Thus, the greatest common divisor of $m$ and $n$ is $2^9 - 1 = \boxed{511}$.
